# core process

### 🇨🇦 Canada — Building Code Development Process

#### A. Governance Structure

| Level                                                          | Actors                                                                                                                                   | Role                                                                                                                                                                    |
|----------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Federal (Model Code Development)                               | - National Research Council (  **NRC**  ) / Canadian Codes Centre  - Canadian Board for Harmonized Construction Codes (  **CBHCC**  )    | Develops and maintains the  **National Model Codes**  : NBC (Building), NECB (Energy), NPC (Plumbing), NFC (Fire). Coordinates consensus committees and public reviews. |
| Provincial / Territorial Governments                           | Ministries responsible for building regulation (e.g., Ontario’s Ministry of Municipal Affairs & Housing, BC’s Ministry of Housing, etc.) | **Adopt and adapt**  National Model Codes into binding law. Some create  **amended versions**  (e.g., Ontario Building Code).                                           |
| Municipal Governments / Authorities Having Jurisdiction (AHJs) | Building officials, inspectors, fire marshals                                                                                            | **Enforce**  provincial codes through permitting, plan review, and inspections. Issue local interpretations and variances.                                              |

#### B. Standards &amp; Technical Foundations

| Type                      | Organizations                                                                                       | Function                                                                                                                                                          |
|---------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Accreditation Body        | Standards Council of Canada (SCC)                                                                   | Accredits Standards Development Organizations (SDOs) and ensures consensus procedures meet ISO/IEC norms.                                                         |
| SDOs (Consensus-based)    | **CSA Group**  ,  **ULC/ULSE**  ,  **BNQ**  ,  **CGSB**  , etc.                                     | Develop  **referenced standards**  (e.g., CSA A23.1 for concrete, CSA O86 for wood, ULC S101 for fire resistance) through multi-stakeholder consensus committees. |
| Professional Associations | **Engineers Canada**  ,  **RAIC**  ,  **CIPH**  ,  **CHBA**  ,  **CaGBC**  ,  **NRCan**  (advisory) | Provide expert input, training, and advocacy. May serve on committees or submit change proposals.                                                                 |

#### C. Process Flow (Model Code to Enforcement)

1. **Priority Setting** – CBHCC consults provinces/territories to define technical priorities (e.g., energy efficiency, resilience, accessibility).
2. **Technical Committees Draft Changes** – Subject-specific committees (e.g., Structural, Fire, Energy) composed of regulators, industry, academia, and professionals.
3. **Public Review Period** – Draft changes open for public comment (typically 60–90 days). All feedback reviewed and adjudicated.
4. **CBHCC Approval &amp; NRC Publication** – Approved changes consolidated into new National Model Codes (~5-year cycle).
5. **Provincial/Territorial Adoption** – Jurisdictions adopt (with or without amendments) via legislation/regulation.
6. **Municipal Implementation** – Local permitting, inspection, and compliance enforcement.
7. **Ongoing Maintenance** – Interpretations, bulletins, STANDATA (Alberta), and interim amendments between editions.

### 🇺🇸 United States — Building Code Development Process

#### A. Governance Structure

| Level                       | Actors                                                                | Role                                                                                                                                              |
|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Model Code Organization     | International Code Council (ICC)                                      | Develops the I-Codes (IBC, IRC, IECC, IFC, IMC, IPC, etc.) through the  **Governmental Consensus Process**  .                                     |
| Standards Developers        | **NFPA**  ,  **ASHRAE**  ,  **ASTM**  ,  **ANSI**  ,  **IES**  , etc. | Provide consensus standards referenced in I-Codes (e.g., ASHRAE 90.1 for energy, NFPA 70 for electrical).                                         |
| Federal Agencies (Advisory) | **DOE**  ,  **EPA**  ,  **HUD**  ,  **FEMA**  ,  NIST                 | Influence scope and research, fund pilot programs, publish determinations on energy savings, but  **do not regulate building codes**  nationally. |
| States &amp; Municipalities | State code councils, city building departments                        | Adopt, modify, and enforce model codes; often with amendments and version lags.                                                                   |

#### B. Consensus and Hearing Process

1. **Proposal Stage** – Anyone (individuals, associations, government bodies, manufacturers) may submit code change proposals to ICC.
2. **Committee Action Hearings (CAH)** – Technical committees review and vote on proposals after public testimony.
3. **Public Comment Period** – Stakeholders submit feedback or revisions to CAH outcomes.
4. **Public Comment Hearings (PCH)** – Additional testimony; governmental members vote to approve or reject.
5. **Online Governmental Consensus Vote (OGCV)** – Verified governmental members finalize code changes.
6. **Validation &amp; Publication** – ICC Board validates process and publishes new edition (every 3 years).
7. **Adoption &amp; Enforcement** – States/municipalities adopt the model codes, often with local amendments.
8. **Maintenance** – Errata, technical interpretations, and interim updates issued.

#### C. Stakeholder Involvement (U.S.)

| Stakeholder                                          | Role in Process                                                                   |
|------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Governmental Members (AHJs)                          | Final voting power in ICC process.                                                |
| Architects / Engineers / Builders / Developers       | Submit proposals, testify at hearings, comment on drafts, serve on committees.    |
| Manufacturers / Trade Associations                   | Supply data, lobby for technical inclusions, sit on balanced-interest committees. |
| Environmental / Energy NGOs (e.g., RMI, ACEEE, NEEP) | Provide research, mobilize advocacy, and influence energy code adoption.          |
| Federal &amp; State Energy Offices                   | Fund code adoption/training programs; DOE issues savings determinations.          |

# comparison

### Comparison: Canada vs. U.S. — Code Development Ecosystem

| Function             | Canada                                                              | United States                                                    |
|----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Model Code Developer | NRC / CBHCC                                                         | ICC                                                              |
| Consensus Structure  | Federal–provincial–territorial with balanced stakeholder committees | Open hearings with final vote restricted to governmental members |
| Referenced Standards | CSA, ULC, BNQ (SCC-accredited)                                      | NFPA, ASHRAE, ASTM, ANSI-accredited                              |
| Adoption Authority   | Provinces and territories                                           | States and municipalities                                        |
| Enforcement          | Municipal building officials (under provincial acts)                | Local AHJs (under state/local law)                               |
| Code Cycles          | ~5 years                                                            | ~3 years                                                         |
| Public Review        | National bilingual review (anyone can comment)                      | Public comment and hearings (anyone can testify)                 |

# res v. non-res overlap and divergence

### Residential vs. Non-Residential — How They’re Addressed

#### 

|                                             | Governing Model Code                                              |                                                                                                                                             |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |                                                                                                                   |                                                                                                                |                                                                                                                                                                                                           |    |
|---------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----|
| **Category**                                | **Canada**                                                        |                                                                                                                                             |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               | **USA**                                                                                                           |                                                                                                                |                                                                                                                                                                                                           |    |
| Residential (housing &amp; small buildings) | **National Building Code, Part 9**  (housing and small buildings) | Prescriptive, focused on 3 storeys or less, ≤ 600 m². Incorporates energy and ventilation provisions (with links to NECB or NBC Part 9.36). | **Overlap:**  Shared objectives (safety, accessibility, energy). Both are part of the same NBC framework, using different parts.  **Divergence:**  Residential governed by simpler, prescriptive rules; non-residential requires engineered design, professional stamps, and NECB compliance. | **International Residential Code (IRC)**                                                                          | Stand-alone model code derived from IBC; prescriptive approach; simplified energy and structural requirements. | **Overlap:**  Both part of ICC’s I-Codes; many provisions (e.g., fire, plumbing) cross-reference each other.  **Divergence:**  IRC covers low-rise, detached dwellings only; IBC governs everything else. |    |
| Non-Residential / Large Buildings           | **NBC Parts 3–8**  ,  National Energy Code for Buildings (NECB)   | Performance-based; integrates structural, fire, and energy provisions; often references CSA standards for assemblies and systems.           |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               | **International Building Code (IBC)**  +  **IECC (commercial chapters)**  +  **Mechanical/Plumbing/Energy Codes** | Performance-based, integrates ASHRAE 90.1 for energy; engineered systems required.                             |                                                                                                                                                                                                           |    |

Overlaps and Divergences

| Dimension                       | Overlap                                                                              | Divergence                                                                                               |
|---------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Core Purpose                    | Life safety, structural integrity, fire protection, accessibility, energy efficiency | Complexity, scale, and performance levels differ                                                         |
| Model Development Process       | Both use consensus-based, multi-stakeholder approaches                               | Canada = intergovernmental + technical committees; U.S. = ICC public hearings with governmental vote     |
| Referenced Standards            | Both rely on independent SDOs                                                        | Different accreditation systems (SCC vs ANSI); differing technical baselines                             |
| Adoption Authority              | Subnational governments                                                              | Provincial/territorial (Canada) vs. state/municipal (U.S.)                                               |
| Residential vs. Non-Residential | Both divide scope by scale and complexity                                            | Canada separates within one model code; U.S. splits into separate codes (IRC vs IBC)                     |
| Practitioner Pathways           | Architects, engineers, and builders influence via committee work and public comment  | In both systems, professionals’ input is non-binding but often influential                               |
| Energy &amp; Carbon Integration | Increasing harmonization (e.g., NECB, IECC)                                          | Divergent implementation pace; Canada’s energy code integrated nationally, U.S. adoption varies by state |

